<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-366-448  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 366 448.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 23 1990 v7 n16 p21(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Open Plan/Mac to meet high-end needs. (Welcom Software Technologyintroduces Mac version of Open Plan project management software)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Welcom Software Technology introduces Open Plan/Mac, a Macintoshversion of its powerful project-management software.andP;  OpenPlan/Mac can schedule up to 10,000 activities, allocate unlimitedresources to any one project, and support up to 256 calendars.andP;  Itstores information in Fox Software Inc's FoxBase+/Mac and isfile-compatible with the DOS and VAX versions of Open Plan, whichuse the Ashton-Tate dBASE language.andP;  Database storage gives theprogram added flexibility not found in other project managementpackages.andP;  Open Plan/Mac is now in beta test and will be availablein late May 1990 at $4,200 for a single-user system.andP;  A four-userLAN version will be released in sum 1990 for $14,000.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Welcom Software Technology (product introduction).andO;Product:   Open Plan/Mac (Project management software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Software packagesProject Management SystemsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;Welcom Software Technology is aiming to fill the hole at the high end of theApple Macintosh project-management market with a Mac version of its Open Plansoftware.andM;Open Plan/Mac offers the same features found in the DOS and Digital EquipmentCorp.andP;  VAX versions of the software, with scheduling of as many as 10,000activities, support for 256 calendars and allocation of unlimited resourcesto any one project, said Courtney Parker, vice president of the Houston-basedcompany.andM;The new program is being beta tested now and will be released by the end ofMay, Parker said.andP;  The program will support the Mac user interface, offeringpull-down menus and allowing users to point and click to access programfeatures, he noted.andM;Because Open Plan/Mac stores data in Fox Software Inc.'s FoxBase+/Mac, filesare compatible with DOS and VAX versions of the project-management program,which are based on Ashton-Tate's dBASE.andM;&quot;The flexibility that a database-based project-management program gives youcan't be found currently in the Mac market,&quot; said Parker.andM;Beta tester Glenn Meyer, a scheduler at University Research Associates'Superconducting Supercollider Laboratory in Dallas, agreed.andP;  &quot;We haven'tfound anything that's as flexible or powerful as Open Plan,&quot; Meyer said.andO;&quot;We're standardized on Macs, but we bought DOS machines just to be able torun Open Plan.andM;&quot;Because Open Plan is built on a database, you can use the database languageto add code fields to the reporting structure,&quot; Meyer said.andP;  &quot;This gives yougreat flexibility in the way you look at data in reports.&quot;andM;Open Plan's advanced resource-scheduling features also put it ahead of otherMac project managers, according to Parker.andM;The Mac project-management market has heated up during the past year, butmost of the new entrants, such as Scitor Corp.'s soon-to-be-released ProjectScheduler 4.0, do not provide the high-end flexibility of Open Plan/Mac.andM;Open Plan/Mac costs $4,200 for a single-user system and $14,000 for afour-user LAN.andP;  The multiuser version will be released this summer.andM;Welcom can be reached at (713) 558-0514.andO;</TEXT></DOC>